<a href=http://www.brellserilis.net/index.shtml>Brell Serilis</a><br>
<br>
<i>Joy is in the ears that hear!</i>
</font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utypan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Typan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/1/01 11:51:22 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Congratulations to Drunks and friends.....</span><hr size=1> True, he didn't let the raiders know he wanted the scale for his bard.  However, he *also* didn't take the bard's odds on the scale either.  The bards got 2 numbers, he got 1.  He could've said &quot;I need the scale for my bard!  I should get 2 numbers too!&quot; but he didn't.  He took the odds given the caster he was playing and won.<br>
<br>
From that point on, it is his scale.  He may use it to make a cloak, or trade it to a bard for whatever he needs.  It just so turns out the bard he traded it to was himself.  I'm as curious as Darksyd about that, would you feel better if he obtained a WSDC and put it on his cleric to complete the trade?<br>
<br>
It is my understanding that the loot rules on the scale were not set before the raid began.  Had the rules been stated beforehand that only bards would get to roll, Faandeg may have mentioned the fact that he would like to roll for his bard who is unable to attend the raid.  Since they weren't, he went with the odds that he was given.  Congratulations Faandeg on attaining this envied/hard-to-get epic piece.  Can't wait to see your sword sing.<br>
